plot(Y_simu, type = 'l')

ar_mdl = ARmdl(Y_simu,ar=2)
ar_mdl$coef
```

## Moment-Based Test  
  
Optional Arguments are:  
  
* p: number of AR(p) lags (default:  1)
* N: Total number of Monte Carlo simulations for p-val calculations (default: 100 which includes the test-stat)
* N2: Number of simulations for distribution approximation (eq. 16 in Dufour & Luger 2017) (default: 10000)
* N3: Number of values to evaluate for nuissance parameters when using 'randSearch_paramCI' in MaxMC (default: 100000).
  
# Monte-Carlo moment-based test.  
  
This takes a few seconds only.  
  
```{r}
start <- Sys.time()
DLMCtest(Y, p = 4)
end   <- Sys.time()
print(end - start)
```
# Maximized Monte-Carlo moment-based test.  
  
In addition to parameters above, available optimization methods can be set using 'searchType'. Allowed options are:  
  
* randSearch_paramCI: This searches over the 95% C.I.of consistent esitmate. This gives similar reuslts to MMC results in Dufour & Luger (2017)
* GenSA: Uses Generalized Simulated Annealing optimization algorithm.
* GA: Uses Genetic Algorithms.
* PSO: Uses Particle Swarm Optimization  
  
```{r}
start <- Sys.time()
DLMMCtest(Y, p = 4, searchType = 'randSearch_paramCI')
end   <- Sys.time()
print(end - start)

start <- Sys.time()
DLMMCtest(Y, p = 4, searchType = 'GenSA')
end   <- Sys.time()
print(end - start)
```
## Carrasco Hu Ploberger (2014) Test 
  
Optional Arguments are:    
   
* p: number of AR(p) lags (default:  1 )
* N: Total number simulations (default: 3000)
* rho: bound for rho (default: 0.7)  
  
# Main CHP test

This version of the test derives the asymptotic distribution of the test under the null and can thus take some time. To get results that are similar to those in the CHP (2014) paper set \(N = 3000\). This should currently take about 2 hours. For convinience, the example below has \(N = 100\) which only takes about 5 mins.  
  
```{r}
start <- Sys.time()
chp1 <- CHPtest(Y, p = 4, N = 3000, var_switch = 0)
end   <- Sys.time()
print(end - start)


start <- Sys.time()
chp2 <- CHPtest(Y2, p = 4, N = 3000, var_switch = 0)
end   <- Sys.time()
print(end - start)


start <- Sys.time()
chp3 <- CHPtest(Y, p = 4, N = 20, var_switch = 0)
end   <- Sys.time()
print(end - start)


start <- Sys.time()
chp4 <- CHPtest(Y2, p = 4, N = 1000, var_switch = 0)
end   <- Sys.time()
print(end - start)


start <- Sys.time()
chp5 <- CHPtest(Y, p = 4, N = 20, var_switch = 1)
end   <- Sys.time()
print(end - start)


start <- Sys.time()
chp6 <- CHPtest(Y2, p = 4, N = 20, var_switch = 1)
end   <- Sys.time()
print(end - start)

```
# Monte-Carlo version of CHP Test  
  
This method makes use of asymptotic distribution of the test under the null and is therefore much faster and  takes only a few seconds regadless of the size of \(N\). 
  
```{r}
start <- Sys.time()
CHPMCtest(Y, p = 4, N = 3000)  
end   <- Sys.time()
print(end - start)
```
  
## Hensen Test  
  
Optional Arguments are:  
  
* p: Number of AR(p) (default is 1).
* ix: List of Markov Switching parameters. 1 = just mean c(1,2) = mean and first param,  (default: 1).
* iv: Idicates if Variance is also Markov Switching. 1 for true (default: 0).
* iq: Indicator that bounds q by 1-p (default: 0).
* gn: Number of different values to evaluate for each param (default: 20)
* rep: (default: 1000)  
  
This takes about 15-20 mins.  
  
```{r}
start <- Sys.time()
HLRtest(Y,p = 4, iv = 1)
end   <- Sys.time()
print(end - start)
```
## LR-Test  
  
Optional Arguments are:  
  
* ar: Number of AR(p) (default is NULL (i.e. no AR)).
* k: number of regimes (default: 2). 
* N: number of simulations is N-1.  
  
# Monte-Carlo Likelihood-Ratio Test  
  
This takes only a few seconds  
  
```{r}
start <- Sys.time()
LRMC_test <-  LRMC_ARMS(Y, ar = 4, k = 2, N = 100)
LRMC_test$pval
end   <- Sys.time()
print(end - start)
```
# Maximized Monte-Carlo Likelihood-Ratio Test  
  
Optimization methods include: 
* GenSa: Uses Generalized Simulated Annealing optimization algorithm.
* randSearch: Does a random search around consistent estimates.  
  
This takes about 8 mins  
  
```{r}
start <- Sys.time()
LRMMC_test <-  LRMMC_ARMS(Y, ar = 2, k = 2, N = 100, method = "GenSA")
LRMMC_test$pval
end   <- Sys.time()
print(end - start)
```

